For any two correlated events, A and B, the different possible relationships include:
BULLET::::- A causes B (direct causation);
BULLET::::- B causes A (reverse causation);
BULLET::::- A and B are consequences of a common cause, but do not cause each other;
BULLET::::- A and B both cause C, which is (explicitly or implicitly) conditioned on;
BULLET::::- A causes B and B causes A (bidirectional or cyclic causation);
BULLET::::- A causes C which causes B (indirect causation);
BULLET::::- There is no connection between A and B; the correlation is a coincidence.

